    <header class="en-lesson__header">
      <h1>The Tale of the Heike <small>(opening passage)</small></h1>
      <p class="en-lesson__byline">
        Anonymous · written down ca. 13th century · transmitted in many recensions
      </p>
      <p class="en-lesson__japanese-link" lang="ja">
        日本語版: <a href="/library/kotoko1/heike-monogatari-gion">平家物語・祇園精舎</a>
      </p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h2>Original Japanese</h2>
      <blockquote class="song" lang="ja">
        <p>
          祇園精舎の鐘の声、諸行無常の響あり。<br />
          沙羅双樹の花の色、盛者必衰のことわりをあらはす。<br />
          おごれる人も久しからず、ただ春の夜の夢のごとし。<br />
          猛き者も遂にはほろびぬ、偏に風の前の塵におなじ。
        </p>
      </blockquote>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>English translation (literal)</h2>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          The bell of the Gion temple resounds with the echo of the impermanence
          of all things.<br />
          The colour of the <em>sāla</em> blossom reveals the truth that the
          prosperous must decline.<br />
          The proud do not last long, but are like a dream on a spring night.<br />
          The mighty fall at the last, like dust before the wind.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="en-lesson__translator-note">
        Translation: project_procopios contributors (CC BY 4.0). This is a literal,
        annotation-friendly rendering. For more lyrical English versions, see
        Helen Craig McCullough\'s and Royall Tyler\'s translations of the full
        <em>Tale of the Heike</em>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Why this passage matters</h2>
      <p>
        The opening of <em>Heike Monogatari</em> (<em>The Tale of the Heike</em>)
        is one of the most famous passages in Japanese literature, comparable in
        cultural weight to the opening of Homer\'s <em>Iliad</em> for Greek tradition,
        or the first line of <em>Beowulf</em> for Old English. Every Japanese
        student encounters it in high school.
      </p>
      <p>
        Three key Buddhist concepts thread through these four lines:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>諸行無常 (shogyō mujō)</strong> — "all phenomena are impermanent."
          Nothing made of conditioned causes can endure unchanged.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>盛者必衰 (jōsha hissui)</strong> — "the prosperous must decline."
          What rises will inevitably fall.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>偏に風の前の塵 (hitoe ni kaze no mae no chiri)</strong> — "purely
          dust before the wind." Even the mighty are no more substantial than
          motes about to scatter.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These three formulas are not abstract philosophy: they are the lens
        through which the <em>Heike</em> recounts the rise and fall of the
        Taira (Heike) clan during the Genpei War of 1180–1185 — a civil war
        that ended the Heian aristocratic order and inaugurated the medieval
        warrior age.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The sāla blossom</h2>
      <p>
        The <em>sāla</em> tree (Sanskrit: <em>śāla</em>; Japanese: <em>shara</em>;
        Latin: <em>Shorea robusta</em>) is the tree under which the Buddha
        died (parinirvāṇa). The legend holds that when the Buddha entered
        nirvana, the four pairs of sāla trees surrounding him turned white
        and their petals fell. In Japanese poetic imagination, the sāla
        thus symbolizes the impermanence even of beauty.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Performance tradition</h2>
      <p>
        For centuries, <em>Heike Monogatari</em> was chanted by blind itinerant
        monks (<em>biwa hōshi</em>) accompanying themselves on the lute-like
        <em>biwa</em>. The text we read today is largely the form fixed by
        that oral performance tradition. The musical rhythm of the original
        prose — alternating 7- and 5-syllable phrases — is built for
        recitation, not silent reading.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Suggested reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Royall Tyler (trans.), <em>The Tale of the Heike</em> (Viking, 2012).</li>
        <li>Helen Craig McCullough (trans.), <em>The Tale of the Heike</em> (Stanford, 1988).</li>
        <li>Paul Varley, <em>Warriors of Japan</em> (1994) for historical context.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

